\end_inset

 are constants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Ideal Gases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ideal gases, the equation of state is given as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pV=n\bar{R}T
\]

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
amount of substance
\noun default
 of the gas (in moles)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{R}=8.3144598(48)~\joulepermolekelvinnp$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
universal gas constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or equivalently
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\rho RT\qquad R=\frac{\bar{R}}{M}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the gas constant for that gas whose 
\noun on
molecular mass
\noun default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
For ideal gases, there are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=e+RT\qquad c_{p}-c_{v}\equiv R\qquad c_{v}=\frac{R}{\gamma-1}\qquad c_{p}=\frac{\gamma R}{\gamma-1}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v},c_{p},\gamma$
\end_inset

 may be functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First Law of Thermodynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Law1ofThermodynamics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Heat put into a system 
\begin_inset Formula $=$
\end_inset

 Increase in internal energy of the system 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 Work done by the system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta q=\dd{e}+p\dd{v}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LHS is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\dd{q}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is not a state variable and the RHS is generally not an 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "exact differential"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exact_differential"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By multiplying an 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "integrating factor"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrating_factor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $1/T$
\end_inset

 and assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

 is added reversibly to the system, the LHS becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\dd{s}$
\end_inset

 (which is a state variable) and the RHS becomes exact:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dd{s}=\frac{\delta q}{T}=\frac{\dd{e}+p\dd{v}}{T}
\]

\end_inset

So, the 1st law of thermodynamics can also be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T\dd{s}=\dd{e}+p\dd{v}=\dd{h}-v\dd{p}\label{eq:Law1ofThermodynamics}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 2nd line comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $h:=e+pv$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second Law of Thermodynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
A process whose only net result is to take heat from a reservoir and convert
 it to work is impossible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Given two heat engines working between 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}<T_{1}$
\end_inset

).
 One is reversible, which takes heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and delivers heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The other is arbitrary, which also takes heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 but delivers heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

' at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{2}\le Q_{2}'\qand W=Q_{1}-Q_{2}>Q_{1}-Q_{2}'=W'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
There is only one reversible heat engine in the world, whose efficiency
 is the highest among all the heat engines, and depends only on the pair
 of temperatures it is running between.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the efficiency of a reversible engine running between a certain temperature
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and a standard temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

 is known, we could work out the efficiency for any other pair of temperatures.
 For a reversible engine running between 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 absorbed at 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 must be proportional to the heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{s}$
\end_inset

 delivered at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q(T)=f(T)\cdot Q_{s}
\]

\end_inset

in which, the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must be a increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1^{\circ})=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 itself as a new scale of temperature, called the 
\noun on
absolute thermodynamic temperature
\noun default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\left(T^{\text{new}}\right)=T^{\text{new}}S\qquad T^{\text{new}}:=f\left(T\right)\cdot T_{s}\qquad S:=\frac{Q_{s}}{T_{s}}
\]

\end_inset

It can be proved that if we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}=1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\text{new}}$
\end_inset

 will be equivalent with that defined by the kinetic theory.
 From now on, we shall use this definition of temperature exclusively, and
 ignore the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\text{new}}$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is called 
\noun on
entropy
\noun default
, which is numerically equal to the heat delivered to a 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

-reservoir.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change of entropy between two states can be calculated by assuming a
 reversible process connecting these two states and integrating the infinitesima
l entropy change along the path of the process.
 This is summarized in the following theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If heat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta Q$
\end_inset

 is added reversibly to a system at a constant temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the increase in entropy of the system is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S=\Delta Q/T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
More generally, during a reversible process 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, if heat 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Q$
\end_inset

 is added to the system when it is at temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the entropy change of the system at that moment is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dd{S}=\delta Q/T$
\end_inset

, and the total entropy change is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S=\int_{C}\left(\delta Q/T\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using the absolute thermodynamic temperature, the unique reversible heat
 engine defines a equivalence relation on the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Q,T\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(Q_{1},T_{1}\right)=\left(Q_{2},T_{2}\right)\qif\frac{Q_{1}}{T_{1}}=\frac{Q_{2}}{T_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

It is clear that this equivalence relation is actually the 
\noun on
isentropic relation
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Using the absolute thermodynamic temperature, the work done by a reversible
 heat engine running between 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}<T_{1}$
\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=Q_{1}-Q_{2}=\left(1-\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\right)Q_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After introducing the concept of entropy, the 2nd law of thermodynamics
 can be restated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
In any irreversible process, the entropy (of the whole world) is increased.
 Only in reversible processes does the entropy (of the whole world) remain
 constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
For a calorically ideal gas (
\begin_inset Formula $p=\rho RT$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e=c_{v}T$
\end_inset

), the change of entropy between two states can be calculated by assuming
 a reversible process connecting the two states and integrating
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dd{s}=\frac{\delta q}{T}=\frac{\dd{e}+p\dd{v}}{T}
\]

\end_inset

which comes from the 1st law of thermodynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Law1ofThermodynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{2}-s_{1}=\int_{T_{1}}^{T_{2}}\frac{c_{v}\dd{T}}{T}-\int_{\rho_{1}}^{\rho_{2}}R\frac{\dd{\rho}}{\rho}=\int_{T_{1}}^{T_{2}}\frac{c_{p}\dd{T}}{T}-\int_{p_{1}}^{p_{2}}R\frac{\dd{p}}{p}
\]

\end_inset

If the gas is also calorically perfect (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v},c_{p}$
\end_inset

 are constants), the integrals have explicit results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{2}-s_{1}=c_{v}\ln\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}-R\ln\frac{\rho_{2}}{\rho_{1}}=c_{p}\ln\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}-R\ln\frac{p_{2}}{p_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

